    <sect1 id="sec.markup.block">
      <title>Block Structures</title>
      <para>
    Block elements include figures, tables, and sections. These elements
    usually create a line break before and after them.
   </para>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.block.figures">
        <title>Figures</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">figure</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/figure.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A figure is a formal example with a title. Figures often contain
        graphics or other large display elements. Frequently, they get IDs
        and are referenced from the text with
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">xref</sgmltag> or
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">link</sgmltag>.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">imageobject</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/imageobject.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        An <sgmltag class="emptytag">imageobject</sgmltag> is a wrapper containing
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">imagedata</sgmltag> and its associated meta
        information.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">imagedata</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/imageobject.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        This element points to an external entity containing graphical image
        data.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">mediaobject</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/mediaobject.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        This element contains a set of alternative <quote>media
        objects</quote>. In DocBook, three types of external objects
        are defined: <sgmltag class="emptytag">videoobject</sgmltag>s,
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">audioobject</sgmltag>s, and
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">imageobject</sgmltag>s. Additional textual descriptions may
        be provided with <sgmltag class="emptytag">textobject</sgmltag>s.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">screenshot</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/screenshot.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A <sgmltag class="emptytag">screenshot</sgmltag> is a graphical
        environment for
        displaying an image of what the user might see on a computer screen.
        It is often used to display application screenshots, dialogs,
        and other components of a graphical user interface.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">textobject</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/textobject.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A <sgmltag class="emptytag">textobject</sgmltag> is a wrapper containing
        a textual description of a media object and its associated metadata.
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">textobject</sgmltag>s are only allowed in
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">mediaobject</sgmltag>s as a fallback option.
        They cannot be the primary content.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <para>
     Always assign an <sgmltag class="attribute">id</sgmltag> attribute to a
     <sgmltag class="emptytag">figure</sgmltag> element.
    </para>
        <para>
     Provide an appropriate image width.
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;figure id="fig.foo"&gt;
  &lt;title&gt;A Foo Picture&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;screenshot&gt;
    &lt;mediaobject&gt;
      &lt;imageobject role="latex"&gt;
       &lt;imagedata fileref="k3b_main.eps" width="80%" format="EPS"/&gt;
      &lt;/imageobject&gt;
      &lt;imageobject role="html"&gt;
       &lt;imagedata fileref="k3b_main.png" width="75%" format="PNG"/&gt;
      &lt;/imageobject&gt;
    &lt;/mediaobject&gt;
  &lt;/screenshot&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;</screen>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.block.examples">
        <title>Examples</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">example</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/example.html"/>
              </para>
              <para><sgmltag class="emptytag">example</sgmltag> is a formal
              example with a title.
        Examples often contain program listings or other large, block
        elements. Frequently, they have IDs and are referenced from the text
        with <sgmltag class="emptytag">xref</sgmltag> or
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">link</sgmltag>.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag>screen</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/screen.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A <sgmltag class="emptytag">screen</sgmltag> is a verbatim environment
        for displaying
        text that the user might see on a computer terminal. It is often
        used to display the results of a command.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <para>
     Always insert an <sgmltag class="attribute">id</sgmltag> attribute
     inside an <sgmltag class="emptytag">example</sgmltag> element.
    </para>
        <para>
     Be careful with the <sgmltag class="emptytag">screen</sgmltag> element:
     Always begin the
     code after the start tag and omit whitespaces before the end tag. Do
     not indent the code. Always start in the first row.
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;example id="ex.foo"&gt;
  &lt;title&gt;A clever presentation of &lt;command&gt;foo&lt;/command&gt;&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;screen&gt;#!/bin/bash
echo "Hello foo"&lt;/screen&gt;
&lt;/example&gt;</screen>
        <para>
     If you need line numbering, insert the attribute
     <sgmltag class="attribute">linenumbering</sgmltag> with the value
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">numbered</sgmltag>. Do not use hardcoded line
     numbers in the <sgmltag class="emptytag">screen</sgmltag> environment.
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;example id="ex.foo"&gt;
  &lt;title&gt;A clever presentation of &lt;command&gt;foo&lt;/command&gt;&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;screen <emphasis role="bold">linenumbering="numbered"</emphasis>&gt;#!/bin/bash
echo "Hello foo"&lt;/screen&gt;
&lt;/example&gt;</screen>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.block.callouts">
        <title>Callouts</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">callout</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/callout.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A <sgmltag class="emptytag">callout</sgmltag> is a visual device for associating
        annotations with an image, program listing, or similar figure. Each
        location is identified with a mark and the annotation is identified
        with the same mark. This is somewhat analogous to footnotes in text.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">calloutlist</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/calloutlist.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A <sgmltag class="emptytag">calloutlist</sgmltag> is a list of annotations or
        descriptions. Each <sgmltag class="emptytag">callout</sgmltag> points to the area on
        a <sgmltag class="emptytag">screen</sgmltag> that it augments.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">co</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/co.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A <sgmltag class="emptytag">co</sgmltag> identifies (by its location) a point of
        reference for a callout.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <para>
     Callouts do not stand alone. They are only useful in combination with
     <sgmltag class="emptytag">screen</sgmltag>. At the moment, <sgmltag class="emptytag">screenco</sgmltag>
     and <sgmltag class="emptytag">arearef</sgmltag> are not supported by
     <command>xsltproc</command>.
     <remark>rwalter:
      Still valid 2006/09/06</remark>
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;screen&gt;
color white/blue black/light-gray   &lt;co id="co.col"/&gt;
default 0   &lt;co id="co.def"/&gt;
timeout 8   &lt;co id="co.time"/&gt;
gfxmenu (hd0,0)/boot/message

title SUSE Linux Enterprise
    kernel (hd0,0)/boot/vmlinuz root=/dev/hda1 vga=0x31a selinux=0
    splash=silent resume=/dev/hda2 desktop elevator=as  showopts
    initrd (hd0,0)/boot/initrd

title Diskette
    root (fd0)
    chainloader +1&lt;/screen&gt;

     &lt;calloutlist&gt;
      &lt;callout arearefs="co.col"&gt;
       &lt;para&gt;Here, define the colors used by the
  &lt;application&gt;GRUB&lt;/application&gt; menu.
       &lt;/para&gt;
      &lt;/callout&gt;
      &lt;callout arearefs="co.def"&gt;
       &lt;para&gt;Define the default option.
       &lt;/para&gt;
      &lt;/callout&gt;
      &lt;callout arearefs="co.time"&gt;
       &lt;para&gt;
  Select a timeout after which booting will start automatically.
       &lt;/para&gt;
      &lt;/callout&gt;
     &lt;/calloutlist&gt;
</screen>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.block.procedures">
        <title>Procedures</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">procedure</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/procedure.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A <sgmltag class="emptytag">procedure</sgmltag> encapsulates a task composed of
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">step</sgmltag>s (and possibly <sgmltag class="emptytag">substep</sgmltag>s).
        Procedures are performed sequentially.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">step</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">substep</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/step.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A step identifies a unit of action in a
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">procedure</sgmltag>. If careful internal procedures are
        required for some steps, you can embed <sgmltag>substep</sgmltag>s
        in a <sgmltag class="emptytag">step</sgmltag>. Embedded <sgmltag class="emptytag">substep</sgmltag>s
        contain <sgmltag class="emptytag">step</sgmltag>s, so that
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">substep</sgmltag>s can be nested to any depth.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <screen>&lt;procedure&gt;
  &lt;title&gt;A Good Procedure&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;step&gt;
    &lt;para&gt;Get up from your bed&lt;/para&gt;
  &lt;/step&gt;
  &lt;step&gt;
    &lt;para&gt;Walk to the kitchen&lt;/para&gt;
  &lt;/step&gt;
  &lt;step&gt;
    &lt;para&gt;Make coffee or tea&lt;/para&gt;
  &lt;/step&gt;
&lt;/procedure&gt;</screen>
        <procedure>
          <title>A Good Procedure</title>
          <step>
            <para>
       Get up from your bed.
      </para>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
       Walk to the kitchen.
      </para>
          </step>
          <step>
            <para>
       Make coffee or tea.
      </para>
          </step>
        </procedure>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.block.qandaset">
        <title>Question and Answers</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">qandaset</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/qandaset.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A <sgmltag class="emptytag">qandaset</sgmltag> is a list consisting of questions and
        answers. <sgmltag class="emptytag">qandaset</sgmltag>s can be divided into sections.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">qandaentry</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/qandaentry.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A <sgmltag class="emptytag">question</sgmltag> in a <sgmltag class="emptytag">qandaentry</sgmltag> poses
  a question or states a problem that is addressed by the following
  <sgmltag class="emptytag">answer</sgmltag>(s).</para>
              <remark>This and question have the same definition.  Please improve
  this. -rwalter</remark>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">question</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/question.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A <sgmltag class="emptytag">question</sgmltag> in a <sgmltag class="emptytag">qandaentry</sgmltag> poses
  a question or states a problem that is addressed by the following
  <sgmltag class="emptytag">answer</sgmltag>s.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">answer</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/answer.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        An <sgmltag class="emptytag">answer</sgmltag> is optional (some questions have
  no answers) and may be repeated (some questions have more than one
  answer).
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <screen>&lt;qandaset&gt;
 &lt;title&gt;Questions and Answers&lt;/title&gt;
 &lt;qandaentry&gt;
  &lt;question&gt;
    &lt;para&gt;Is equality important?&lt;/para&gt;
  &lt;/question&gt;
  &lt;answer&gt;
    &lt;para&gt;Yes.&lt;/para&gt;
   &lt;/answer&gt;
 &lt;/qandaentry&gt;
&lt;/qandaset&gt;</screen>
        <qandaset>
          <title>Questions and Answers</title>
          <qandaentry>
            <question>
              <para>Is equality important?</para>
            </question>
            <answer>
              <para>Yes.</para>
            </answer>
          </qandaentry>
        </qandaset>
      </sect2>
    </sect1>
    <sect1 id="sec.inline">
      <title>Inline Structures</title>
      <para>
    Inline elements include keys, menus, and commands. These elements are
    usually used inside text. They do not impose a line break.
   </para>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.inline.keys">
        <title>Markup of Keys</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">keycap</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/keycap.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        The <sgmltag class="emptytag">keycap</sgmltag> identifies the letter or symbol
        printed on a physical key on a computer keyboard.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">keycombo</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/keycombo.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        For actions that require multiple keystrokes, mouse actions, or
        other physical input selections, the <sgmltag class="emptytag">keycombo</sgmltag>
        element provides a wrapper for the entire set of events.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <para>
     Mark up keys with the element <sgmltag class="emptytag">keycap</sgmltag>:
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;para&gt;
  Press &lt;keycap&gt;F2&lt;/keycap&gt; to ... Use the &lt;keycap
  function="control"/&gt; key.
&lt;/para&gt;</screen>
        <para>
     If you mark up modifier keys, the keys next to Insert, cursor keys, or
     <keycap function="enter"/>, <keycap function="backspace"/>, or
     <keycap function="escape"/>, use the
     <sgmltag class="attribute">function</sgmltag> attribute. Possible
     attribute values for
     <sgmltag class="attribute">function</sgmltag> are
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">alt</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">backspace</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">command</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">control</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">delete</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">down</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">end</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">enter</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">escape</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">home</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">insert</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">left</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">meta</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">option</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">other</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">pagedown</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">pageup</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">right</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">shift</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">space</sgmltag>,
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">tab</sgmltag>, and
     <sgmltag class="attvalue">up</sgmltag>.
     When using the function attribute, make the tag self-closing&mdash;DocBook's
     language files will insert key names automatically. This simplifies both
     your work and translation.
    </para>
        <para>
     If you need key combinations (you press two or more keys at the same
     time or after a short period), use <sgmltag class="emptytag">keycombo</sgmltag>. Use the
     <sgmltag class="attribute">action</sgmltag> attribute to distinguish
     between different actions:
    </para>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><sgmltag class="attvalue">press</sgmltag> (default action) </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
        If you omit the <sgmltag class="attribute">action</sgmltag>
        attribute, this value is used:
       </para>
              <screen>&lt;para&gt;
  Press &lt;keycombo&gt; &lt;keycap function="alt"/&gt;
  &lt;keycap&gt;F2&lt;/keycap&gt; &lt;/keycombo&gt; to ...
&lt;/para&gt;</screen>
              <literallayout>Press <keycombo><keycap function="alt"/><keycap>S</keycap></keycombo> to ...</literallayout>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="attvalue">seq</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
        Use this if you need keys pressed sequentially, for example, those
        in Emacs:
       </para>
              <screen>&lt;para&gt;
To save a file in Emacs, press &lt;keycombo action="seq"&gt;
   &lt;keycombo action="press"&gt;
     &lt;keycap function="control"/&gt;
     &lt;keycap&gt;X&lt;/keycap&gt;
   &lt;/keycombo&gt;
   &lt;keycombo&gt;
     &lt;keycap function="control"/&gt;
     &lt;keycap&gt;S&lt;/keycap&gt;
   &lt;/keycombo&gt;
 &lt;/keycombo&gt;.
&lt;/para&gt;</screen>
              <literallayout>To save a file in Emacs, press <keycombo action="seq"><keycombo action="press"><keycap function="control"/><keycap>X</keycap></keycombo><keycombo><keycap function="control"/><keycap>S</keycap></keycombo></keycombo>.</literallayout>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="attvalue">click</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="attvalue">double-click</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="attvalue">other</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="attvalue">simul</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
        These are not used in SUSE documentation.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.inline.menus">
        <title>GUI Menus</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">guimenu</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/guimenu.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        SUSE uses this element to simplify GUI element markup. It is used
        for all types of menu entries and also for buttons and GUI labels.
       <remark>taroth 2014-01-03: what about titles of dialogs? I often use it
         for those, too - should that be avoided or is it allowed?</remark></para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <screen>&lt;para&gt;
     Use the &lt;guimenu&gt;File&lt;/guimenu&gt; menu to reach the
     &lt;guimenu&gt;Print&lt;/guimenu&gt; option.
&lt;/para&gt;</screen>
        <literallayout>Use the <guimenu>File</guimenu> menu to reach the <guimenu>Print</guimenu> option.</literallayout>
        <para>
     To mark up nested menu structures, use <sgmltag class="emptytag">menuchoice</sgmltag>:
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;para&gt;
 To exit Emacs, use &lt;menuchoice&gt;
   &lt;guimenu&gt;File&lt;/guimenu&gt;
   &lt;guimenu&gt;Exit Emacs&lt;/guimenu&gt;
  &lt;/menuchoice&gt;.
&lt;/para&gt;</screen>
        <literallayout>To exit Emacs, use <menuchoice><guimenu>File</guimenu><guimenu>Exit Emacs</guimenu></menuchoice>.</literallayout>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.inline.commands">
        <title>Commands and Options</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">command</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/command.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        This element holds the name of an executable program or the text of
        a command that a user enters to execute a program.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">option</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/option.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        This element identifies an argument to a command or instruction.
        Options may or may not be required.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <para>
     Use options for a command inside <sgmltag class="emptytag">command</sgmltag>. Be careful
     about spaces:
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;command&gt;xmllint &lt;option&gt;--help&lt;/option&gt;&lt;/command&gt;</screen>
        <literallayout>
          <command>xmllint <option>--help</option></command>
        </literallayout>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.inline.vars">
        <title>Variables</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">replaceable</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/replaceable.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        Content that may or must be replaced by the user.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <para>
     Use <sgmltag class="emptytag">replaceable</sgmltag> to tag contents that should be
     replaced by appropriate user input. For example:
    </para>
        <literallayout>Use <command>ls <option><replaceable>my_dir</replaceable></option></command> to list the contents of the directory <replaceable>my_dir</replaceable>.</literallayout>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.inline.filenames_and_dirs">
        <title>Directories and File names</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">file name</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/filename.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        A file name is the name of a file on a local or network disk. It could
        be a simple name or could include a path or other elements specific to
        the operating system.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <para>
     Because SUSE does not distinguish between file names and directories (by
     adding a trailing slash to the path or with markup),
     <sgmltag class="emptytag">filename</sgmltag> is used for both directories and file names.
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;para&gt;
 See file &lt;filename&gt;foo.xml&lt;/filename&gt;. Look at the
 directory &lt;filename&gt;/etc/sysconfig&lt;/filename&gt;.
&lt;/para&gt;</screen>
        <literallayout>See file <filename>foo.xml</filename>. Look at the directory <filename class="directory">/etc/sysconfig</filename>.
    </literallayout>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.inline.referencing">
        <title>Referencing</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">ulink</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/ulink.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        The <sgmltag class="emptytag">ulink</sgmltag> element forms the equivalent of an HTML
        anchor (<sgmltag class="starttag">A HREF="..."</sgmltag>) for cross
        reference by a Uniform Resource Locator (URL).
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">xref</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/xref.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        The <sgmltag class="emptytag">xref</sgmltag> element forms a cross-reference from the
        location of the <sgmltag class="emptytag">xref</sgmltag> to the element to which it
        points. Unlike the other cross-referencing elements,
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">xref</sgmltag> is empty. The processing system must
        generate appropriate cross-reference text for the reader.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <para>
     References to man pages and info pages should generally be made in the
     format <quote>the man page of <command>command</command></quote> or
     <quote>the info page of <command>command</command></quote>. In a
     situation where the category of the page is needed, add
     <quote>(<command>man 9 command</command>)</quote> to the end.
    </para>
        <literallayout>See the man page of <command>xmllint</command> (<command>man 1 xmllint</command>).</literallayout>
        <para>
     Use <sgmltag class="emptytag">ulink</sgmltag> to reference to a URL:
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;para&gt; See &lt;ulink url="http://www.suse.de"/&gt;. See &lt;ulink
     url="http://www.novell.de"&gt;Novell Deutschland&lt;/ulink&gt;.</screen>
        <literallayout>See <ulink url="http://www.suse.de"/>. See <ulink url="http://www.novell.de">Novell Deutschland</ulink>.
    </literallayout>
        <para>
     If you need references to another chapter, section, etc., in the same
     documentation set, use <sgmltag class="emptytag">xref</sgmltag>:
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;para&gt; A link to this section: &lt;xref
     linkend="sec.markup.inline.referencing"/&gt; &lt;/para&gt;</screen>
        <literallayout>A link to this section: <xref linkend="sec.markup.inline.referencing"/>
    </literallayout>
        <remark>toms (TBD): How do we use the attribute <sgmltag class="attribute">xrefstyle</sgmltag>?</remark>
        <para>
     If you need a different text for referencing purposes, but you cannot
     modify the title, use the
     <sgmltag class="attribute">xreflabel</sgmltag> attribute:
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;sect1 id="sec.foo" <emphasis role="bold">xreflabel="Hello foo"</emphasis>&gt;
  &lt;title&gt;Foo&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;para&gt;...&lt;/para&gt;

&lt;/sect1&gt;
  ...
&lt;para&gt;See <emphasis role="bold">&lt;xref linkend="chap.foo"/&gt;</emphasis>...&lt;/para&gt;</screen>
        <para>
     In the above example, the <sgmltag class="emptytag">xref</sgmltag> is
     replaced by the text <literal>Hello foo</literal>.
    </para>
        <remark>please add a description of xreflabel used to reference otherwise unlabeled elements
     like listitems etc.</remark>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.inline.emphasis">
        <title>Emphasis</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">emphasis</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/emphasis.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        This element provides a method for indicating that certain text
        should be stressed in some way. However, placing emphasis with
        careful wording is preferred to using markup.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <para>
     Use bold text with care.
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;para&gt;
  This is a &lt;emphasis&gt;strongly emphasized&lt;/emphasis&gt; word.
  This is a &lt;emphasis role="bold"&gt;very strongly
  emphasized&lt;/emphasis&gt; word.
&lt;/para&gt;</screen>
        <literallayout>This is a <emphasis>strongly emphasized</emphasis> word.
This is a <emphasis role="bold">very strongly emphasized</emphasis> word.</literallayout>
      </sect2>
      <sect2 id="sec.markup.inline.comments">
        <title>Comments and Remarks</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">remark</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/remark.html"/>
              </para>
              <para>
        The <sgmltag class="emptytag">remark</sgmltag> element is designed to hold remarks,
        such as editorial comments, that are useful while the document is in
        the draft stage, but are not intended for final publication.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="sgmlcomment">An XML comment</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
        XML comments are used to hold remarks. They are invisible in your
        publication.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <para>
     Use <sgmltag class="emptytag">remark</sgmltag>s for comments that you can switch on or
     off in HTML or PDF. Place a <sgmltag class="emptytag">remark</sgmltag> before or after
     the <sgmltag class="emptytag">para</sgmltag> to comment. Otherwise you would insert
     unwanted line breaks.
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;remark&gt;A small remark&lt;/remark&gt;</screen>
        <literallayout>
          <remark>A small remark.</remark>
        </literallayout>
        <para>
     Use XML comments if you give translators or other editors some hints
     that should only be visible in the code, but not in the final
     publication&mdash;even for a draft state.
    </para>
        <screen>&lt;para&gt; &lt;!-- Is this true? Please check! --&gt; If you need X,
     you must install Y before you can use it. &lt;/para&gt;</screen>
        <literallayout>If you need X, you must install Y before you can use it.</literallayout>
        <para>
     Be short and clear with your comments.
    </para>
      </sect2>

      <sect2>
        <title>Indexterms</title>

        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">indexterm</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/indexterm.html"/>
              </para>
              <para><sgmltag class="emptytag">indexterm</sgmltag>s identify text that is to be
                placed in the <sgmltag class="emptytag">index</sgmltag>. In the simplest case,
                the placement of the <sgmltag class="emptytag">indexterm</sgmltag> in the
                document identifies the location of the term in the text.
                In other words, the <sgmltag class="emptytag">indexterm</sgmltag> is placed
                in the flow of the document at the point where the
                <sgmltag class="emptytag">indexentry</sgmltag> in the Index should point.
                In other cases, attributes on <sgmltag class="emptytag">indexterm</sgmltag> are
                used to identify the location of the term in the text.
              </para>

              <example id="ex.indexplain">
                <title>A Plain Index Entry</title>
                <screen>&lt;para&gt;
  To configure DNS&lt;indexterm&gt;
    &lt;primary&gt;DNS&lt;/primary&gt;
    &lt;secondary&gt;configuring&lt;/secondary&gt;
  &lt;/indexterm&gt;, use …
&lt;/para&gt;</screen>
              </example>

              <example id="ex.index.range">
                <title>An Index Range</title>
                  <screen>&lt;indexterm <emphasis role="bold">class="startofrange" id="idx.Installation"</emphasis>&gt;
  &lt;primary&gt;installing&lt;/primary&gt;
    &lt;/indexterm&gt;
…
&lt;indexterm <emphasis role="bold">class="endofrange" startref="idx.Installation"</emphasis>/&gt;</screen>
              </example>
              <example id="ex.index.see">
                <title>A See Index Entry</title>
                  <screen>&lt;indexterm&gt;
  &lt;primary&gt;installing&lt;/primary&gt;
    &lt;secondary&gt;boot loaders&lt;/secondary&gt;
     <emphasis role="bold">&lt;see&gt;GRUB&lt;/see</emphasis>&gt;
&lt;/indexterm&gt;</screen>
              </example>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
      </sect2>

      <sect2 id="sec.markup.inline.literal">
        <title>Literals</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>
              <sgmltag class="emptytag">literal</sgmltag>
            </term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.docbook.org/tdg/en/html/literal.html"/>
              </para>
              <para><sgmltag class="emptytag">literal</sgmltag> is specific data taken literally from a
        computer system. It is similar in some ways to
        <sgmltag class="emptytag">userinput</sgmltag> and <sgmltag class="emptytag">computeroutput</sgmltag>,
        but is somewhat more general a classification.
       </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
        <screen>&lt;para&gt;
  If you need a comment, insert &lt;literal&gt;#&lt;/literal&gt; characters.
&lt;para&gt;</screen>
      </sect2>
    </sect1>
</appendix>